4 SYNOPSIS:
5 This bill would recreate the Alabama Commission
6 on the Evaluation of Services as a legislative
7 department and substantially revise provisions
8 governing the operation of the commission.
9 This bill would provide for the appointment of
10 the director of the commission and revise and clarify
11 certain duties of the commission.
12 This bill would also establish the Legislative
13 Committee on the Evaluation of Services to supervise
14 and control the commission.
15
16
17 A BILL
18 TO BE ENTITLED
19 AN ACT
20
21 Regarding the Alabama Commission on the Evaluation of
22 Services; to add Chapter 2B to Title 29, Code of Alabama 1975,
23 to recreate the commission as a legislative department; to
24 substantially revise the provisions governing the operation of
25 the commission; to provide for the appointment of a director;
26 to revise and clarify duties of the commission; to create the
27 Legislative Committee on the Evaluation of Services; to repeal
28 Chapter 2A, Title 29, Code of Alabama 1975, the existing law
Page 1

Chapter 2A, Title 29, Code of Alabama 1975, the existing law
29 governing the commission; and to provide an effective date.
30 BE IT ENACTED BY THE LEGISLATURE OF ALABAMA:
31 Section 1. Chapter 2B is added to Title 29, Code of
32 Alabama 1975, to read as follows:
33 Chapter 2B. Alabama Commission on the Evaluation of
34 Services.
35 §29-2B-1
36 There is created the Alabama Commission on the
37 Evaluation of Services, which shall be a legislative
38 department, for the purpose of advising the Legislature
39 regarding the evaluation of services funded by the state.
40 §29-2B-2
41 (a) The affairs of the commission shall be administered
42 by the director, whose actions shall be supervised and
43 controlled by the Legislative Committee on the Evaluation of
44 Services. The director shall be selected and appointed by the
45 committee and shall receive compensation and benefits in an
46 amount established by the committee, payable in the same
47 manner as is provided for other state employees.
48 (b) A vacancy in the office of director arising from
49 any cause shall be filled by the committee. The committee may
50 appoint a highly qualified person as its director to a
51 nonmerit, conditional appointment. The director, with the
52 consent and approval of the committee, shall select and
53 supervise professional and clerical staff upon a full-time or
54 part-time basis as necessary to assist the committee and the
55 director in performing the duties assigned by this chapter.
56 The director, without regard to the state Merit System Act,
Page 2

The director, without regard to the state Merit System Act,
57 may hire employees as necessary to effectuate the purposes of
58 this chapter. The number of employees, their compensation, and
59 other expenditures of the committee shall be within the limits
60 and in compliance with the appropriation made therefor by the
61 Legislature and within budgets that shall be approved from
62 time to time by the commission.
63 §29-2B-3
64 (a) There is hereby established the Alabama Commission
65 on the Evaluation of Services Fund in the State Treasury for
66 the deposit of all funds received by the commission and which
67 shall be used for the operations of the commission.
68 (b) The commission may receive state appropriations and
69 apply for and receive grant funds from other sources
70 including, but not limited to, foundations, governmental
71 entities, federal grants, and businesses. No public monies
72 shall be expended by the director for any purpose unless the
73 monies have been appropriated by the Legislature to the
74 commission. Any monies appropriated shall be budgeted and
75 allotted pursuant to the Budget Management Act in accordance
76 with Article 4 of Chapter 4 of Title 41, and only in the
77 amounts provided by the Legislature in the general
78 appropriations act or other appropriation acts.
79 §29-2B-4
80 (a) The commission shall conduct evaluations of any
81 agency or programs, services, activities, or functions of any
82 agency at the direction of the Legislative Committee on the
83 Evaluation of Services. Evaluations may include oversight and
84 performance audits or evaluations pursuant to 45 CFR Part 164
Page 3

performance audits or evaluations pursuant to 45 CFR Part 164
85 E or 39 CFR Part 99 Subpart D.
86 (b) Any agency, or third party contractor to an agency,
87 shall furnish to the commission any available material, which
88 the commission determines to be necessary in the performance
89 of the duties and functions of the commission.
90 (c) Any collection of data by an agency, or third party
91 contractor to an agency, shall be furnished to the commission
92 upon request by the director or an employee of the commission.
93 (d) The commission may take application for and award
94 grant funds to any agency to further the purposes, policies,
95 recommendations, and objectives of the commission subject to
96 the availability of funding.
97 §29-2B-5
98 For purposes of this chapter, the following terms have
99 the following meanings:
100 (1) AGENCY. Any department, board, commission, office,
101 institution, or other unit of state government that receives
102 appropriations from the state.
103 (2) CAUSAL IMPACT EVALUATION. A rigorous evaluation
104 that uses experimental or quasi-experimental methods to
105 determine whether a program caused observed outcomes,
106 isolating the program's effects from other factors.
107 (3) EVALUATION PLAN. A written document that describes
108 how an agency will assess a program's implementation, outputs,
109 and outcomes, including the data sources, indicators, and
110 methods to be used.
111 (4) LOGIC MODEL. A visual or narrative representation
112 that shows the logical relationships between a program's
Page 4

that shows the logical relationships between a program's
113 resources, activities, outputs, and intended outcomes.
114 (5) MAJOR EXPANSION. An increase in a program's
115 appropriation of 25 percent or more compared to the prior
116 fiscal year, or an expansion that significantly changes the
117 program's target population, service delivery method, or
118 geographic scope.
119 (6) NEW PROGRAM. A program that receives an
120 appropriation for the first time and that is not a
121 continuation or modification of an existing program under a
122 different name or organizational structure.
123 (7) PRELIMINARY STUDY. An evaluation or examination of
124 a proposed or existing policy or program conducted before or
125 during legislative consideration, designed to inform
126 legislative decisions about program design, feasibility, or
127 resource requirements.
128 (8) PRIORITY EVALUATION QUESTION. A significant
129 question about a program's implementation, effectiveness, or
130 outcomes that an agency or the commission identifies as
131 warranting systematic evaluation.
132 §29-2B-6
133 The Alabama Commission on the Evaluation of Services
134 shall develop and publish on its website the evaluation
135 standards used in the performance of evaluations.
136 §29-2B-7
137 (a) Each year, within 30 days of the conclusion of the
138 regular session of the Legislature, or any special session
139 where an appropriations act is enacted, the Legislative
140 Services Agency shall identify each new program or major
Page 5

Services Agency shall identify each new program or major
141 expansion of an existing program for which an agency received
142 an appropriation and notify the agency and the Alabama
143 Commission on the Evaluation of Services of the programs
144 subject to the provisions of this chapter.
145 (b) Each agency shall prepare an evaluation plan for
146 each new program and each major expansion of an existing
147 program that is enacted in an appropriations act, as follows:
148 (1) The evaluation plan shall, at a minimum, describe
149 the program's objectives, target population, key activities,
150 expected inputs, outputs, intended outcomes, and benchmarks
151 for intended outcomes. These variables shall be incorporated
152 into a logic model in the plan.
153 (2) The evaluation plan shall identify the indicators
154 the agency will use to track inputs, outputs, and key
155 outcomes; and for each, describe the data sources and explain
156 how the measures will be calculated for each indicator.
157 (3) The evaluation plan shall classify the planned
158 level of evaluation (for example, monitoring, outcome
159 evaluation, or causal impact evaluation) consistent with the
160 typology in the standards issued under Section 29-2B-6.
161 (4) For programs meeting criteria established in
162 guidance under Section 29-2B-6, the evaluation plan shall
163 include a proposal for a causal impact evaluation or a
164 justification for why such an evaluation is not feasible or
165 appropriate.
166 (5) Evaluation plans shall be submitted to the Alabama
167 Commission on the Evaluation of Services for approval and
168 publication on its website, per the standards and guidance
Page 6

publication on its website, per the standards and guidance
169 issued under Section 29-2B-6, before data is analyzed.
170 §29-2B-8
171 (a) For each program subject to this chapter, the
172 agency shall prepare and submit evaluation reports to the
173 Alabama Commission on the Evaluation of Services on a schedule
174 specified in the standards issued under Section 29-2B-6, which
175 shall include at a minimum:
176 (1) A description of the program as implemented,
177 including any material deviations from the original evaluation
178 plan;
179 (2) Results on the agreed-upon input, output, and
180 outcome indicators, including baseline values and trends over
181 time;
182 (3) For programs with a causal impact evaluation, a
183 summary of the evaluation design, key findings, and
184 limitations; and
185 (4) The agency's interpretation of the findings and
186 planned actions in response (for example, continuation,
187 expansion, modification, or termination).
188 (b) The Alabama Commission on the Evaluation of
189 Services shall publish submitted evaluation reports on its
190 website.
191 §29-2B-9
192 The Legislature, by language in an appropriations act
193 or other act, may require an evaluation of a specific program
194 or line item. Such a provision may:
195 (1) Specify that no more than a stated percentage of
196 funds may be expended until the agency has submitted an
Page 7

funds may be expended until the agency has submitted an
197 evaluation plan meeting the standards of this chapter;
198 (2) Require that an evaluation report be submitted by a
199 certain date and that continuation, renewal, or expansion of
200 funding in a subsequent fiscal year shall consider the
201 findings; or
202 (3) Identify any additional or different indicators or
203 evaluation questions that are particularly important for the
204 program in question.
205 §29-2B-10
206 (a) The Legislature, by request of the Joint
207 Legislative Committee on Finances and Budget or by language in
208 an appropriations act or other act, may direct the Alabama
209 Commission on the Evaluation of Services to conduct a
210 preliminary study of proposed or existing policies or
211 programs.
212 (b) Any action directing a preliminary study shall
213 specify:
214 (1) The policy or program to be examined; and
215 (2) The questions or issues the study should address.
216 (c) The Alabama Commission on the Evaluation of
217 Services shall coordinate with the respective agencies or
218 entities impacted by the study to:
219 (1) Confirm the scope and objectives of the study;
220 (2) Establish a timeline for completion based on study
221 complexity and available resources;
222 (3) Identify necessary resources, including estimated
223 costs and staffing needs; and
224 (4) Determine the content and format of the final
Page 8

(4) Determine the content and format of the final
225 report.
226 (d) If the Alabama Commission on the Evaluation of
227 Services determines that completing a preliminary study as
228 specified would require resources or time periods that exceed
229 available capacity of the commission or agency, the commission
230 may propose to the Legislature modifications to the study
231 scope, timeline, or resource allocation.
232 (e) Preliminary studies may examine:
233 (1) The feasibility of proposed programs or policies;
234 (2) Estimated costs and potential fiscal impacts;
235 (3) Experiences with similar programs in other
236 jurisdictions;
237 (4) Available data and evidence related to the policy
238 area;
239 (5) Evaluation design options if the policy or program
240 is enacted; or
241 (6) Expected implementation challenges and resource
242 requirements.
243 (f) Each preliminary study report shall include:
244 (1) A description of the policy or program examined;
245 (2) The study methodology and data sources used;
246 (3) Key findings addressing the questions specified in
247 the directing act;
248 (4) Limitations of the analysis; and
249 (5) Implications for policy design or implementation,
250 if applicable.
251 (g) Upon completion, the Alabama Commission on the
252 Evaluation of Services shall publish the preliminary study
Page 9

Evaluation of Services shall publish the preliminary study
253 report on the commission's website and submit the report to
254 the Senate Finance and Taxation Committees, the House Ways and
255 Means Committees, the Legislative Committee on the Evaluation
256 of Services, and the Legislative Fiscal Officer.
257 §29-2B-11
258 (a) There is hereby created a continuing legislative
259 committee to be known as the Legislative Committee on the
260 Evaluation of Services to exercise general supervision and
261 control over the actions of the Alabama Commission on the
262 Evaluation of Services.
263 (b) The committee shall be led by the Chair of the
264 Senate Finance and Taxation General Fund Committee, the Chair
265 of the House Ways and Means General Fund Committee, the Chair
266 of the Senate Finance and Taxation Education Committee, and
267 the Chair of the House Ways and Means Education Committee who
268 shall alternate as the chair of the committee each year.
269 (c) The Alabama Legislative Committee on the Evaluation
270 of Services shall have 12 members. The membership of the
271 committee shall include the following:
272 (1) The Chair and Vice-chair of the Senate Finance and
273 Taxation Education Committee.
274 (2) The Chair and Vice-chair of the Senate Finance and
275 Taxation General Fund Committee.
276 (3) The Chair and Vice-chair of the House Ways and
277 Means Education Committee.
278 (4) The Chair and Vice-chair of the House Ways and
279 Means General Fund Committee.
280 (5) One member of the Senate, appointed by the
